122,Steady drop in HIV positive cases,2016-11-30T11:21:33+05:30,"NASHIK: The overall awareness about HIV/AIDS is reflecting in the drop in the number of HIV positive cases in the district. This year, only 0.68% people tested out of the total suspected cases at various government medical facilities across Nashik district were diagnosed HIV positive. 

Officials of the District AIDS Prevention and Control Unit (DAPCU) said the graph of HIV positive rate has shown a steady decline over the past seven-eight years. They attributed the drop to the rising awareness among people about HIV infection and the facilities available at various government centres. 

Yogesh Pardeshi, district programme officer of DAPCU, said, “Earlier, there used to be special private care centres for HIV positive cases. Over the years, the need of such centres is no longer felt as the people are directly admitted to the government facility for further treatment. The stigma attached to the disease is also fast vanishing.”

He said HIV testing facilities were available at the two general hospitals, four sub-divisional hospitals, 24 rural hospitals and 104 public health centres, urban health hubs, four corporation hospitals, various sub-centres and council hospitals in the district. 

Over the past few years, DAPCU has increased the rate of checking people and pregnant women. 

“The general client testing has been witnessing the drop since 2009, when the rate of HIV positive cases was 4.50%. It dropped to 1.60% in 2012 and 1% in 2014. In 2015, the rate was 0.77%,” he said. 

Even the HIC positivity rate among women has been on a decline since 2006. This year, till October-end, DAPCU has recorded only 0.03% HIV positive women from the total 1,18, 211 checked. 

Nonetheless, six HIV positive babies were identified this year compared to three such instances in 2015. Pardeshi said a new programme has been launched, wherein an HIV positive pregnant woman is immediately brought under treatment that eliminates the chances of transmission of the disease do the baby during pregnancy, delivery or breast feeding. 

“The check on babies is done only after 18 months of birth. The new medication programme was started in 2014 and we will start finding the results from this year. We are hoping for a zero-HIV- infection transfer from the mother to the child,” an official added.


