Counselling is the backbone of HIV management. Counsellors provide information about HIV/AIDS and facilitate behaviour change communication in the client. In addition, they provide psychological support required to address HIV/AIDS-related stigma and discrimination against people living with HIV. 

“Quality training is essential for building and sustaining the capacity of counsellors to provide relevant information and psycho-social support to clients. Till 2013-14, NACO initiated Project Saksham by Tata Institute of Social Sciences with the support of global funds to fight AIDS, tuberculosis and malaria. The counsellors need induction training on priority basis,” read UP government’s letter to NACO. 

Founder of UP Welfare for Persons Living with HIVAIDS Society and HIV issues trainer Naresh Yadav said, “The counselling process and parameters will have to be reworked as they address primary issues but not related questions. For example, a counsellor tells you to eat medicines come what may, but have almost nothing to say if you talk about side effects. Similarly, they talk about what to do but not how to cope with it.”

