149,"Patient groups, legal experts express concern over HIV/AIDS Bill",2017-03-23T18:32:25+05:30,"Patient groups, legal experts and activists have expressed concern over the HIV/AIDS (Prevention and Control) Bill, saying it dilutes the Central and state government’s obligation to provide complete treatment to HIV patients. The Bill which was passed in Rajya Sabha on March 21, failed to ensure free and complete treatment to People Living with HIV, as it states that government shall provide treatment to HIV patients ‘as far as possible’.

An obligation to provide treatment ""as far as possible"" is a significant dilution of the right of people living with HIV to treatment, which is well known that it must be taken life-long. 

The National AIDS Control Organisation provides free screening and treatment to HIV patients in centres across the country. 

Deletion of the clause from section 14(1) has been a major demand by patients and experts since the Bill was tabled in Rajya Sabha in February 2014. Though several MPs moved amendments to remove these words, these were regrettably withdrawn at the last minute. It should be noted that a mere verbal assurance by the government that treatment would not be denied to any person is not equivalent to a legal obligation, experts added. 

Anand Grover, director Lawyers Collective (LC) said “There are few issues also which need to be addressed but the primary one which had to be addressed deleting the words, “as far possible” in Clause 14(1) relating to treatment measures. It is extremely unfortunate that despite the overwhelming support for this was not pursued. The LC strongly urges the minister to delete those words as also look into other glitches in the Bill which have already been pointed out.”

The Bill under Section 14 (1) only states that Central and state government shall take measures to `as far as possible’ provide anti-retroviral treatment, diagnostics and treatment for HIV patients, estimated to be over two million. 

Says Loon Gangte regional coordinator-South Asia International Treatment Preparedness Coalition: The Health Minister’s verbal assurance that no one will be denied treatment as India will adopt ""test and treat"" policy, is very welcoming but this has no constitutional or legal status. We want concrete assurance and safeguard of our treatment in the Indian Constitution”.

Paul Lhungdim president, The Delhi Network of Positive People said: Today, entire Rajya Sabha failed the HIV community in India. The Congress Party shamefully withdrew the amendment they themselves had suggested, at the last minute. Politicians have betrayed us, which will have adverse effect on future treatment of people living with HIV in India. The government does not provide treatment for co-infections like Hepatitis C and opportunistic infections like Kaposi Sarcoma, a form of cancer”.

