163,Youngsters haven’t stopped working for HIV/AIDS patients,2017-07-23T22:47:52+05:30,"The number of HIV/AIDS patients has steadily decreased in the past two years in Maharashtra and credit for that goes to thousands of young health workers, who are working with complete dedication in this field. The sad part is that most of them have not been paid their monthly stipend for more than seven months and yet they haven’t stopped working. We tell you all about their trauma, trials and tribulations…
Sheel Maske (name changed on request) is pursuing his masters in social sciences, but his passion is — easing the agony of those suffering from AIDS. He works as a health worker while pursuing his studies privately. But these days, tension is writ large on his face. Ask him the reason and he shares, “My friends and I get a monthly stipend of `5000. This helps us in travelling to various parts of the city and beyond, spreading awareness about AIDS and giving medicines to those who need it. But we haven’t been paid for almost eight months now. Since I come from a stark middle class family, I can’t ask my parents to help me and I can’t ditch the AIDS patients either. So I have borrowed money from friends; I don’t know how long I will be able to continue like this.”
There are others, who are striving hard to survive in these tough times. Akash Ninawe, a 25-year-old, who is pursuing BSW from a night college, laments, “My parents are very fragile medically, so I take care of the home expenses with my meagre stipend. With money not coming for several months now, things are really sad. I have borrowed from various sources because I can’t even afford to pay for my fee or some of the basic amenities.”
There are some homemakers who are working for HIV/AIDS patients and things have been equally tough for them too. Hemlata Lohave, who has been working for AIDS control in the city for long, shares, “I have borrowed money from loan sharks to make the two ends meet and it is tough running a home in this situation. The sad part is that some of the senior officers of District AIDS Control Unit and Technical Support Unit tell us to quit and not crib about non-payment of dues.” When we contacted programme officer, Nagpur district, Tanuja Fale, she merely said, “I just look after the administration and not the payments.” When we reminded her that payments are also a part of administration, she went on to say, “We hope that the money will be released at the end of this month.” 
Joint director of Maharashtra State Aids Control Society (MSACS), Dr Lokesh Gabhane, however, gave an assurance. “I have worked with the health workers and I understand their pain. It is commendable that these people have been sending their monthly reports on time, this shows their level of commitment. Due to backlog of last year and a half, the problem of non-payment has persisted, but I assure everyone that by next week, the payments will be remitted in people’s accounts directly. This year, the payments will be released every four months and we will get the pending payments also cleared, it’s my promise.”

"
164,Gujarat sees hope in AIDS survivors,2016-12-01T06:18:20+05:30,"AHMEDABAD: She is a battle-hardened mother who exemplifies life amid all hurdles. In March 2000, soon after having tested HIV positive, she gave birth to a son who also was diagnosed with the same disease. In 2005 she lost her husband to AIDS but that too did not see her falter. Armed with an iron-will she took up his job as a cable operator and battled on with her son who is now 17 year old. “I urge people like me to live a healthy life with proper medical treatment,” she said.

